		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">The description of weather systems fits naturally into a Lagrangian framework; forecasters think of parcels of air moving about in the atmosphere, producing weather phenomena.  Rearrangements arise naturally when considering the Lagrangian description of fluid flow.  We propose to tackle the following specific problems using ideas from rearrangement theory:a) mathematical formulation of forecast error decomposition into a combination of displacement (of, for example, an event), and a difference in qualitative features:b) demonstrate existence and properties of atmospheric models where some physical quantity, typically potential vorticity, is conserved following the motion; in particular, by weakening regularity assumptions to allow treatment of nonsmooth solutions:a) extend existing theory of solutions of the semo geostrophic equations, as a sequence of minimum energy states, to spherical geometry.We further propose to study the interplay between Hamiltonian and rearrangement methods.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
